Topix Rises for the First Time in Three Days as Crude Oil Prices Retreat

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   H i d e k i   S a g i i k e
-- 
2011-03-09T07:30:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-09/topix-rises-for-the-first-time-in-three-days-as-crude-oil-prices-retreat.html
Japanese stocks advanced, sending
the Topix index to its first gain in three days, as a decline in  oil prices  eased concern higher energy costs will impede the
global economic recovery.  Nippon Yusen K.K. , Japan’s No. 1 shipping line, climbed
1.7 percent as cargo rates increased and oil prices eased for a
second day. Nintendo Co., the world’s largest maker of video-
game players, jumped 3.7 percent, after saying a new game set a
sales record. Bridgestone Corp., the biggest tiremaker, advanced
3.1 percent after Citigroup Inc. raised the stock’s target price.  “Crude oil futures have stopped rising for the moment and
that’s eased uncertainty somewhat,” said  Hiroichi Nishi , an
equities manager at Nikko Cordial Securities Inc. in Tokyo.
“The global economy is recovering and companies are showing
better earnings.”  The Topix increased 0.6 percent to 944.29 at the 3 p.m.
close in Tokyo, paring gains after rising earlier as much as 1.3
percent. The  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average rose 0.6 percent 10,589.50.  Shipping lines gained after the Baltic Dry Index of cargo
rates increased for an eighth consecutive day to the highest
level since Jan. 18. Nippon Yusen rallied 1.7 percent to 352 yen.
Mitsui O.S.K. Lines Ltd., Japan’s second-largest shipper,
advanced 0.8 percent to 536 yen.  OPEC Mulling Talks  Sheikh Ahmad al-Abdullah al-Sabah,  Kuwait ’s oil minister,
yesterday told reporters that the OPEC secretariat is
considering holding talks on increasing production amid supply
disruptions in  Libya . Crude for April delivery decreased as much
as 81 cents to $104.21 a barrel in electronic trading on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange  today.  Nintendo jumped 3.7 percent to 23,800 yen after saying it
sold more than 1.08 million new Pokemon games in the first day
of sales. The previous one-day sales record for the series was
about 780,000, according to the company.  Tiremakers and other producers of rubber products rose the
most on the Topix after Citigroup boosted price estimates for
Bridgestone and Sumitomo Rubber Industries Ltd. Bridgestone
climbed 3.1 percent to 1,773 yen. Sumitomo Rubber, Japan’s
second-largest tiremaker, jumped 3.4 percent to 912 yen.  Maker’s of factory equipment also gained after a report
showed machinery orders rose more than economists expected in
January, signaling manufacturers plan to boost investment. Fanuc
Corp., Japan’s No. 1 maker of industrial robots, advanced 0.6
percent to 12,880 yen. Industrial sewing-machine maker Juki Corp.
added 5.4 percent to 215 yen.  Yokogawa, Machinery Orders    Yokogawa Electric Corp. (6841) , a maker of electronic measuring
tools, jumped 5.6 percent to 665 yen, the biggest gain on the
Nikkei, after Mizuho Securities Co. raised its investment rating
to “outperform” from “underperform.”  Bookings for equipment, an indicator of  capital spending  in
three to six months, increased 4.2 percent from December, when
they rose 1.7 percent, the Cabinet Office said today in Tokyo.
Orders were projected to climb 3 percent, according to the
median forecast of 28 economists surveyed by Bloomberg News.  The Topix has gained 5.1 percent this year on signs the
global economy is recovering and as more companies reported
earnings that exceeded analysts’ estimates. The advance compares
with gains of 5.1 percent by the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index and
2.2 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.  Space Shower Networks Inc., a satellite and cable TV
company, surged after saying it will tie-up with KDDI Corp.,
Japan’s second-biggest mobile phone carrier. Space Shower
increased by its daily limit of 5,000 yen, or 19 percent, to
30,650 yen. KDDI advanced 3 percent to 555,000 yen.  Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group Inc., which has a San
Francisco-based  subsidiary , gained 1.4 percent to 449 yen after
Bank of America Corp. said yesterday its home-loan business is
in “recovery mode.”  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 